body.plain:
The strange, shimmering star at the center of the early 2000s psych-pop revival, Animal Collective garnered both critical plaudits and rabid, devoted acolytes by blending Brian Wilson-esque vocal harmonies with spaced-out instrumentation, tribal percussion and odd ribbons of sound.

The band consists of Avey Tare (David Portner), Panda Bear (Noah Lennox), Deakin (Josh Dibb), and Geologist (Brian Weitz).

body.plain:
This is a personal song for Lennox as he talks about his focus on his family. The “girls” are his wife, and his daughter who was born in 2005.

The song grows from a synth-speckled, half-speed intro into a booming electro-pop burner with handclaps and deep bass – a towering edifice of sound.

body.plain:
The 2nd single off of Animal Collective’s absolutely stunning LP, Strawberry Jam is “postmodern lyrical and poetic experimentation.”

It seems to start with the morning after a night of possible drinking, the singer appears to be taking about his love, and although all he wants is to be with them, he doesn’t really know if he finds meaning in it.

body.plain:
“FloriDada” was inspired in part by antagonism towards Floridians by outsiders. The song challenges conceptions of economic privilege and geopolitical boundaries, infusing principles of the twentieth century art movement, Dadaism, to convey its message of longing for a unified view of humanity that also boils down to individual relationships as well. As Avey Tare said:

I heard a radio show in L.A. and they started talking about how the name of the program was ‘What All the Dumb Things People Are Doing in Florida Right Now.’ I was just like, ‘That sucks. Why does everything have to be so negative? Why is everything so “I’m from the South, you’re from the North?”

The lead single for Animal Collective’s tenth album, Painting With, features Avey Tare and Panda Bear quickly trading off vocal duties set to the band’s traditionally exuberant, experimental pop rhythms.

body.plain:
The Afro-Brazilian-flavored “Brother Sport” moves from one chanted melodic nugget to the next before building to a huge swirl of psychedelic sound that encompasses rave sirens and immersive tribal drums.

As the title suggests, the song is about Noah Benjamin Lennox' brother—specifically it is meant as an encouragement.

The words “sport brother”, which are repeated as a sort of mantra, are close to being a homophone of “support (your) brother”.

body.plain: “Summertime Clothes” talks about an intense romance during summertime. The surging thrust of distortion and 4-on-the-floor drumkick that propels the song starts with an almost militaristic pomp, but it soon reaches a place of pure sweetness with a simple chorus hook that could have come from any point in the last 100 years.

annotatable.link_title: For Reverend Green by Animal Collective

body.plain:
For Reverend Green was lauded as one of the songs that demonstrated Avey Tare’s growth as a vocalist, as seen in Pitchfork. However, not many people have elaborated on the meaning of this song.

For Reverend Green is an intentionally misheard lyric for “Forever and Green,” which unrealistically deals with transience, the idea that decay is inevitable.

In For Reverend Green, Avey contrasts the miserable lifestyles perpetuated by the adult society to the oblivious joy and carelessness that is seen in childlike innocence

body.plain: Who Could Win A Rabbit is track 2 on the 2004 album Sung Tongs and was the first single released as a solo effort by the then two-piece band Animal Collective. It was released to moderate popularity and high critical acclaim on July 19, 2004, and is regarded as one of Animal Collective’s early breakthrough hits. The band has never made a specific meaning clear about the song, but it seems to be a message to take life slower and chill out.

description.plain:
The strange, shimmering star at the center of the early 2000s psych-pop revival, Animal Collective garnered both critical plaudits and rabid, devoted acolytes by blending Brian Wilson-esque vocal harmonies with spaced-out instrumentation, tribal percussion and odd ribbons of sound.

The band consists of Avey Tare (David Portner), Panda Bear (Noah Lennox), Deakin (Josh Dibb), and Geologist (Brian Weitz).
